  // Cultural Section
  afrocontemporaneoCulturalHistoryTitle: 'History and Technique of Afro Contemporary (DCC)',
  afrocontemporaneoCulturalShort:
    'Learn Afro Contemporary (Contemporary Dance of Cuba) with the Farray MethodÂ®: exclusive pedagogy created by Yunaisy Farray (ENA Cuba) adapted for Europeans. Original DCC technique (Ramiro Guerra, 1959) with optimized progression for faster and stronger results.',
  afrocontemporaneoCulturalFull: `### The Farray MethodÂ®: DCC Adapted for Europeans

**The Farray MethodÂ® is an exclusive pedagogical system created by Yunaisy Farray to teach Afro Contemporary more solidly and effectively to European dancers.** Yunaisy, a Cuban trained at the National School of Art of Cuba (ENA), detected that the original Cuban methodologyâ€”designed for bodies that grow up dancing from childhoodâ€”needed to be adapted to the European context, where students arrive with different bodily and cultural backgrounds.

**"Farray MethodÂ® (Barcelona): DCC/ENA pedagogy adapted to European bodies; structured progression for faster and more solid results than traditional methodology."**

### The Origins: Contemporary Dance of Cuba (DCC, 1959)

**Afro Contemporary is the pedagogical name for Contemporary Dance of Cuba (DCC), founded by Ramiro Guerra in 1959.** This revolutionary discipline fuses **Martha Graham** techniques with Afro-Cuban roots (Yoruba rumba), and was officially systematized at the **ENA (National School of Art) in 1962**. The first generation of teachers includes figures such as **MÃ©ndez and Collazo (1959)**.

**"Afro Contemporary / DCC (1959, Ramiro Guerra): Graham + Afro-Cuban polyrhythm, ENA 1962."**

### Technical Fusion

What makes Afro Contemporary unique is its ability to integrate seemingly opposite elements:

- **Modern technique**: Contraction-release (Graham), fluidity (LimÃ³n), spatiality (Cunningham)
- **Cuban folklore**: Rumba undulations, energy of the Yoruba Orishas, Afro-Caribbean polyrhythm
- **Body expression**: Deep movement-music connection that goes beyond pure technique

**"DCC = Graham/LimÃ³n/Cunningham fusion + Yoruba rumba; hybrid technique requiring mastery of both worlds."**

### Music: Afro-Cuban Polyrhythm

**Afro Contemporary is practiced to music that fuses Afro-Cuban rhythms (batÃ¡, rumba, son) with contemporary compositions.** The characteristic polyrhythm requires the dancer to develop complex musicality and an interpretive capacity that goes beyond simple counting.

**"Afro-Cuban polyrhythm (batÃ¡, rumba, son) fused with contemporary music; rhythmic complexity develops advanced musicality."**

### Why the Farray MethodÂ® Works Better in Europe

**Yunaisy Farray adapted her ENA training for the European context**, creating a pedagogical progression that:

- **Builds the foundation from scratch**: Does not assume the student has years of prior training
- **Works body dissociation progressively**: Specific exercises for bodies that did not grow up with polyrhythm
- **Integrates technical explanation with practice**: More analytical methodology than traditional Cuban, adapted to European learning

**"Farray MethodÂ® (Yunaisy Farray, ENA Cuba â†’ Barcelona): pedagogical progression specifically designed for European dancers; faster results than traditional ENA methodology."**

### International Recognition CID-UNESCO

The Afro Contemporary taught at **Farray's International Dance Center** is part of the professional dance training curriculum **endorsed by the CID-UNESCO** (International Dance Council, Paris). This recognition certifies both the authenticity of the DCC technique and the effectiveness of the Farray MethodÂ® for its teaching.

**"Farray's Center: only academy in Barcelona with Afro Contemporary (DCC) CID-UNESCO endorsed + exclusive Farray MethodÂ®."**

### Living Legacy: 65 Years of DCC

**Contemporary Dance of Cuba (DCC)** has been bringing Afro Contemporary to stages worldwide since the 1970s. With **65 years of international tours (2024)**, the company has consolidated Afro-modern Cuban fusion as one of Cuba's most valuable contributions to world dance. The Farray MethodÂ® brings this tradition to Barcelona with optimized pedagogy.

**"DCC: 65 years exporting Afro-modern Cuban fusion. Farray MethodÂ® brings this tradition to Europe with adapted pedagogy."**

### Physical and Cognitive Benefits

**Scientific studies on technical dance indicate that disciplines like Afro Contemporary improve complex motor coordination, proprioception, muscle memory, and body dissociation capacity, in addition to cardiovascular and flexibility benefits.**

**An Afro Contemporary class can burn 300-480 calories per hour depending on body weight and intensity, with simultaneous work on strength, flexibility, and cardiovascular endurance.**

**Farray's International Dance Center: Afro Contemporary (DCC) with exclusive Farray MethodÂ®, CID-UNESCO endorsement, 5/5 Google rating with over 500 reviews.**`,

